<p><b>Puma SE</b>, branded as <b>Puma</b>, is a German <a href="/wiki/Multinational_corporation" title="Multinational corporation">multinational corporation</a> that designs and manufactures athletic and casual footwear, apparel and accessories, which is headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Herzogenaurach" title="Herzogenaurach">Herzogenaurach</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bavaria" title="Bavaria">Bavaria</a>, <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a>. Puma is the third largest <a href="/wiki/Sportswear_(activewear)" class="mw-redirect" title="Sportswear (activewear)">sportswear</a> manufacturer in the world.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Top_3_Brands_in_Sportswear_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Top_3_Brands_in_Sportswear-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The company was founded in 1948 by <a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Dassler" title="Rudolf Dassler">Rudolf Dassler</a>. In 1924, Rudolf and his brother <a href="/wiki/Adolf_Dassler" title="Adolf Dassler">Adolf "Adi" Dassler</a> had jointly formed the company <i>Gebrüder Dassler Schuhfabrik</i> (Dassler Brothers Shoe Factory). The relationship between the two brothers deteriorated until the two agreed to split in 1948, forming two separate entities, <i><a href="/wiki/Adidas" title="Adidas">Adidas</a></i> and <i>Puma</i>. Both companies are currently based in Herzogenaurach, Germany.
</p><p>Puma has been a public company since 1986, listed on the <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt_Stock_Exchange" title="Frankfurt Stock Exchange">Frankfurt Stock Exchange</a>. French luxury group <a href="/wiki/Kering" title="Kering">Kering</a> (formerly known as Pinault-Printemps-Redoute or PPR) holds 16%, Kering's largest shareholder Artemis SA owns 29% of the share capital.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Since 1 July 2013, the company has been led by former football professional Bjørn Gulden (chief executive officer).
</p><p>As of 2017, Puma SE employs more than 13,000 people worldwide and distributes its products in more than 120 countries.<sup id="cite_ref-At_a_glance_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-At_a_glance-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-cloudfront1_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cloudfront1-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Following the split from his brother, Rudolf originally registered the newly established company as <i>Ruda</i> (derived from <i><b>Ru</b></i>dolf <i><b>Da</b></i>ssler, as Adidas was based on Adi Dassler), but later changed the name to <i>Puma</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmit200931_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmit200931-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Puma's earliest logo consisted of a square and beast jumping through a <i>D</i>, which was registered, along with the company's name, in 1948. Puma's shoe and clothing designs feature the Puma logo and the distinctive "Formstrip" which was introduced in 1958.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmit200933_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmit200933-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sponsorships">Sponsorships</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Sponsorships">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Puma_sponsorships" title="List of Puma sponsorships">List of Puma sponsorships</a></div>
<p>Puma offers products for <a href="/wiki/Basketball" title="Basketball">Basketball</a>, <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">Football</a>, <a href="/wiki/Running" title="Running">Running</a>, Training and Fitness, <a href="/wiki/Golf" title="Golf">Golf</a>, Motorsports and Sportstyle. It has sponsored a number of legendary athletes, including <a href="/wiki/Pel%C3%A9" title="Pelé">Pelé</a>, <a href="/wiki/Eus%C3%A9bio" title="Eusébio">Eusébio</a>, <a href="/wiki/Johan_Cruyff" title="Johan Cruyff">Johan Cruyff</a>, <a href="/wiki/Diego_Maradona" title="Diego Maradona">Diego Maradona</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lothar_Matth%C3%A4us" title="Lothar Matthäus">Lothar Matthaus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Walt_Frazier" title="Walt Frazier">Clyde Frazier</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jim_Hines" title="Jim Hines">Jim Hines</a>, <a href="/wiki/Boris_Becker" title="Boris Becker">Boris Becker</a>, <a href="/wiki/Martina_Navratilova" title="Martina Navratilova">Martina Navratilova</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tommie_Smith" title="Tommie Smith">Tommie Smith</a>, <a href="/wiki/Joe_Namath" title="Joe Namath">Joe Namath</a>, <a href="/wiki/Linford_Christie" title="Linford Christie">Linford Christie</a>, <a href="/wiki/Colin_Jackson" title="Colin Jackson">Colin Jackson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heike_Drechsler" title="Heike Drechsler">Heike Drechsler</a> and <a href="/wiki/Michael_Schumacher" title="Michael Schumacher">Michael Schumacher</a> among others.
</p><p>Currently, international footballers, including <a href="/wiki/Neymar" title="Neymar">Neymar</a>,
<a href="/wiki/Sergio_Ag%C3%BCero" title="Sergio Agüero">Sergio Agüero</a>, <a href="/wiki/Antoine_Griezmann" title="Antoine Griezmann">Antoine Griezmann</a>, <a href="/wiki/Marco_Reus" title="Marco Reus">Marco Reus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Romelu_Lukaku" title="Romelu Lukaku">Romelu Lukaku</a>, <a href="/wiki/Luis_Su%C3%A1rez" title="Luis Suárez">Luis Suárez</a>, <a href="/wiki/David_Silva" title="David Silva">David Silva</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vincent_Kompany" title="Vincent Kompany">Vincent Kompany</a> and many more are sporting Puma football boots.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In terms of football clubs, Puma sponsors <a href="/wiki/Borussia_Dortmund" title="Borussia Dortmund">Borussia Dortmund</a>, <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City F.C.</a>, <a href="/wiki/Olympique_de_Marseille" title="Olympique de Marseille">Olympique de Marseille</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sociedade_Esportiva_Palmeiras" title="Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras">Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras</a>, <a href="/wiki/Borussia_M%C3%B6nchengladbach" title="Borussia Mönchengladbach">Borussia Mönchengladbach</a>, <a href="/wiki/Crystal_Palace_F.C." title="Crystal Palace F.C.">Crystal Palace F.C.</a>, <a href="/wiki/Newcastle_United_F.C." title="Newcastle United F.C.">Newcastle United F.C.</a>, <a href="/wiki/Valencia_CF" title="Valencia CF">Valencia CF</a>, <a href="/wiki/AC_Milan" class="mw-redirect" title="AC Milan">AC Milan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Club_de_F%C3%BAtbol_Monterrey" class="mw-redirect" title="Club de Fútbol Monterrey">Club de Fútbol Monterrey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bengaluru_FC" title="Bengaluru FC">Bengaluru FC</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mumbai_City_FC" title="Mumbai City FC">Mumbai City FC</a> and many others. National football teams include Italy, Iceland, Switzerland, Austria, Morocco, Egypt and Uruguay.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In athletics (track and field), Puma sponsors several athletic associations such as the <a href="/wiki/Jamaica_Athletics_Administrative_Association" title="Jamaica Athletics Administrative Association">Jamaica</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cuban_Athletics_Federation" title="Cuban Athletics Federation">Cuba</a>, Bahamas, <a href="/wiki/Grenada_Athletic_Association" title="Grenada Athletic Association">Grenada</a>, Trinidad &amp; Tobago, Dominican, Barbados, Portugal, Switzerland and Norway. It also has the world's fastest man and Jamaican track athlete <a href="/wiki/Usain_Bolt" title="Usain Bolt">Usain Bolt</a> under contract along with other track and field athletes like <a href="/wiki/Andre_De_Grasse" title="Andre De Grasse">Andre Degrasse</a>, Karsten Warholm and Gianmarco Tamberi. Over the past decades, several world records were achieved by athletes wearing Puma shoes, such as <a href="/wiki/Heinz_F%C3%BCtterer" title="Heinz Fütterer">Heinz Futterer</a> (1954), <a href="/wiki/Armin_Hary" title="Armin Hary">Armin Hary</a> (1960), <a href="/wiki/Jim_Hines" title="Jim Hines">Jim Hines</a> (1976), <a href="/wiki/Tommie_Smith" title="Tommie Smith">Tommie Smith</a> (1968), <a href="/wiki/Asafa_Powell" title="Asafa Powell">Asafa Powell</a> (2005), and Usain Bolt (2009).<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2018 Puma announced its entrance back into basketball after a break of almost 20 years. The brand appointed <a href="/wiki/Jay-Z" title="Jay-Z">Jay-Z</a> as creative director of Puma basketball.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Marvin_Bagley_III" title="Marvin Bagley III">Marvin Bagley</a>, <a href="/wiki/Deandre_Ayton" title="Deandre Ayton">Deandre Ayton</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zhaire_Smith" title="Zhaire Smith">Zhaire Smith</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Michael_Porter_Jr." title="Michael Porter Jr.">Michael Porter Jr.</a> are the first players to join Puma's basketball roster and play in performance Puma basketball shoes.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also, Puma made its partnership with Netball after 28 years by sponsoring the <a href="/wiki/Melbourne_Vixens" title="Melbourne Vixens">Melbourne Vixens</a>, the only netball team to be partnered with the global firm<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 2018 Puma became the official apparel sponsor of New Zealand's national netball team, the Silver Ferns.
</p><p>The firm sponsors Indian cricketer <a href="/wiki/Virat_Kohli" title="Virat Kohli">Virat Kohli</a> the captain of the <a href="/wiki/India_cricket_team" class="mw-redirect" title="India cricket team">India cricket team</a>. Golfers such as <a href="/wiki/Rickie_Fowler" title="Rickie Fowler">Rickie Fowler</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bryson_DeChambeau" title="Bryson DeChambeau">Bryson DeChambeau</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lexi_Thompson" title="Lexi Thompson">Lexi Thompson</a> are equipped by Puma's golf brand Cobra Puma Golf.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In Formula 1, Puma equips the teams of <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_Formula_One" title="Mercedes-Benz in Formula One">Mercedes AMG Petronas</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scuderia_Ferrari" title="Scuderia Ferrari">Scuderia Ferrari</a> and <a href="/wiki/Red_Bull_Racing" title="Red Bull Racing">Red Bull Racing</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> In addition, Puma also sponsors BMW and Porsche in all its Motorsports activities.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In order to support its women's business, Puma endorses supermodel <a href="/wiki/Cara_Delevingne" title="Cara Delevingne">Cara Delevingne</a> and Adriana Lima as well as actress/singer <a href="/wiki/Selena_Gomez" title="Selena Gomez">Selena Gomez</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Locations">Locations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Locations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The company has a few dozen small corporate offices around the world, and four "international hubs": <a href="/wiki/Boston,_Massachusetts" class="mw-redirect" title="Boston, Massachusetts">Boston, Massachusetts</a> (moving to <a href="/wiki/Assembly_Row" class="mw-redirect" title="Assembly Row">Assembly Row</a>, Somerville, Massachusetts<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup>); <a href="/wiki/Hong_Kong" title="Hong Kong">Hong Kong</a>; <a href="/wiki/Ho_Chi_Minh_City" title="Ho Chi Minh City">Ho Chi Minh City</a>, Vietnam; and global headquarters in <a href="/wiki/Herzogenaurach" title="Herzogenaurach">Herzogenaurach</a>, Germany.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Background">Background</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Background">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Christoph von Wilhelm Dassler was a worker in a <a href="/wiki/Shoe_factory" class="mw-redirect" title="Shoe factory">shoe factory</a>, while his wife Pauline ran a small laundry in the <a href="/wiki/Franconia" title="Franconia">Franconian</a> town of <a href="/wiki/Herzogenaurach" title="Herzogenaurach">Herzogenaurach</a>, 20&#160;km (12.4&#160;mi) from the city of <a href="/wiki/Nuremberg" title="Nuremberg">Nuremberg</a>. After leaving school, their son, <a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Dassler" title="Rudolf Dassler">Rudolf Dassler</a>, joined his father at the shoe factory. When he returned from fighting in <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a>, Rudolf was trained as a salesman at a <a href="/wiki/Porcelain" title="Porcelain">porcelain</a> factory, and later in a leather trading business in <a href="/wiki/Nuremberg" title="Nuremberg">Nuremberg</a>.
</p><p>In 1924, Rudolf and his younger brother, <a href="/wiki/Adolf_Dassler" title="Adolf Dassler">Adolf</a>, nicknamed "Adi", founded a shoe factory. They named the new business "Gebrüder Dassler Schuhfabrik" (<i>Dassler Brothers Shoe Factory</i>) which was the only business at the time that manufactured sports shoes. The pair started their venture in their mother's laundry. At the time, electricity supplies in the town were unreliable, and the brothers sometimes had to use pedal power from a stationary bicycle to run their equipment.<sup id="cite_ref-DW_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DW-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> In 1927, they moved into a separate building.
</p><p>The brothers drove from Bavaria to the <a href="/wiki/1936_Summer_Olympics" title="1936 Summer Olympics">1936 Summer Olympics</a> in Berlin with a suitcase full of spikes and persuaded United States sprinter <a href="/wiki/Jesse_Owens" title="Jesse Owens">Jesse Owens</a> to use them, the first sponsorship for an African American. Owens won four gold medals. Business boomed; the Dasslers were selling 200,000 pairs of shoes annually before World War II.<sup id="cite_ref-rediff_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rediff-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Both brothers joined the <a href="/wiki/Nazi_Party" title="Nazi Party">Nazi Party</a>, but Rudolf was slightly closer to the party. A growing rift between the brothers reached a breaking point during a 1943 Allied bomb attack. Adi and his wife climbed into a bomb shelter that Rudolf and his family were already in. "Here are the bloody bastards again," Adi remarked, apparently referring to the Allied war planes, but Rudolf, due to his apparent insecurity, was convinced his brother meant him and his family.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmit200918_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmit200918-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> When Rudolf was later picked up by American soldiers and accused of being a member of the <a href="/wiki/Waffen_SS" class="mw-redirect" title="Waffen SS">Waffen SS</a>, he was convinced that his brother had turned him in.<sup id="cite_ref-DW_27-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DW-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1948">1948</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: 1948">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>After increasingly different views of how to run the business, the <a href="/wiki/Dassler_brothers_feud" title="Dassler brothers feud">brothers split</a> the business in 1948. Rudolf moved to the other side of the <a href="/wiki/Aurach_(river)" class="mw-redirect" title="Aurach (river)">Aurach River</a> to start his own company. Adolf started his own company using a name he formed using his nickname—Adi—and the first three letters of his last name—Das—to establish <a href="/wiki/Adidas" title="Adidas">Adidas</a>. Rudolf created a new firm that he called "Ruda", from "Ru" in Rudolf and "Da" in Dassler. A few months later, Rudolf's company changed its name to Puma Schuhfabrik Rudolf Dassler in 1948.<sup id="cite_ref-Fundinguniverse_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fundinguniverse-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg/220px-Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg/330px-Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg/440px-Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3648" data-file-height="2736" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_Jago_Zig_Zag_Running_Shoe.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>A pair of Puma sport-lifestyle shoes with the company's distinctive "Formstrip" design</div></div></div>
<p>Puma and Adidas entered a fierce and bitter rivalry after the split. The town of Herzogenaurach was divided on the issue, leading to the nickname "the town of bent necks"—people looked down to see which shoes strangers wore.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1948, the first football match after World War II, several members of the <a href="/wiki/West_Germany_national_football_team" class="mw-redirect" title="West Germany national football team">West German national football team</a> wore Puma boots, including the scorer of West Germany's first post-war goal, <a href="/wiki/Herbert_Burdenski" title="Herbert Burdenski">Herbert Burdenski</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1952">1952</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: 1952">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Rudolf developed a football boot with screw-in studs, called the "Super Atom" in collaboration with people, such as West Germany's national coach <a href="/wiki/Sepp_Herberger" title="Sepp Herberger">Sepp Herberger</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>At the <a href="/wiki/1952_Summer_Olympics" title="1952 Summer Olympics">1952 Summer Olympics</a>, <a href="/wiki/1500_metres" title="1500 metres">1500 metres</a> runner <a href="/wiki/Josy_Barthel" title="Josy Barthel">Josy Barthel</a> of <a href="/wiki/Luxembourg" title="Luxembourg">Luxembourg</a> won Puma's first Olympic gold in <a href="/wiki/Helsinki" title="Helsinki">Helsinki</a>, Finland.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1960">1960</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: 1960">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>At the <a href="/wiki/1960_Summer_Olympics" title="1960 Summer Olympics">1960 Summer Olympics</a> Puma paid German sprinter <a href="/wiki/Armin_Hary" title="Armin Hary">Armin Hary</a> to wear Pumas in the 100-metre sprint final. Hary had worn Adidas before and asked Adolf for payment, but Adidas rejected this request. The German won gold in Pumas but then laced up Adidas for the medals ceremony, to the shock of the two Dassler brothers. Hary hoped to cash in from both, but Adi was so enraged he banned the Olympic champion.<sup id="cite_ref-rediff_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rediff-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:John_Carlos,_Tommie_Smith,_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/John_Carlos%2C_Tommie_Smith%2C_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg/220px-John_Carlos%2C_Tommie_Smith%2C_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="308" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/John_Carlos%2C_Tommie_Smith%2C_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg/330px-John_Carlos%2C_Tommie_Smith%2C_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/John_Carlos%2C_Tommie_Smith%2C_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg/440px-John_Carlos%2C_Tommie_Smith%2C_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg 2x" data-file-width="640" data-file-height="896" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:John_Carlos,_Tommie_Smith,_Peter_Norman_1968cr.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Puma sponsored gold medalist <a href="/wiki/Tommie_Smith" title="Tommie Smith">Tommie Smith</a> (center) and bronze medalist <a href="/wiki/John_Carlos" title="John Carlos">John Carlos</a> (right) showing the <a href="/wiki/Raised_fist" title="Raised fist">raised fist</a> on the podium after the 200&#160;m race at the <a href="/wiki/1968_Summer_Olympics" title="1968 Summer Olympics">1968 Summer Olympics</a>; both wear <a href="/wiki/Olympic_Project_for_Human_Rights" title="Olympic Project for Human Rights">Olympic Project for Human Rights</a> badges.</div></div></div>
<p>During the <a href="/wiki/1968_Olympics_Black_Power_Salute" class="mw-redirect" title="1968 Olympics Black Power Salute">1968 Olympics Black Power Salute</a>, Puma sponsored African-American athletes <a href="/wiki/Tommie_Smith" title="Tommie Smith">Tommie Smith</a> and <a href="/wiki/John_Carlos" title="John Carlos">John Carlos</a>, after having won gold and bronze in the 200 meters respectively, took to the podium with their Puma Suedes in hand and bowed their heads and raised their black-gloved fists in silent protest during the playing of the national anthem, an act meant to stand up for human rights and to stand up for black Americans.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1986">1986</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: 1986">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Puma became a public company in 1986,<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> and thereafter was listed on the <a href="/wiki/B%C3%B6rse_M%C3%BCnchen" title="Börse München">Börse München</a> and <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt_Stock_Exchange" title="Frankfurt Stock Exchange">Frankfurt Stock Exchange</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-PUMA®_–_History_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PUMA®_–_History-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> It also introduced the RS Computer shoe, with "RS" standing for "running system," an integrated device that measured runner's speed, pace, and caloric use. It sold poorly.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1989">1989</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: 1989">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In May 1989, Rudolf's sons Armin and Gerd Dassler agreed to sell their 72 percent stake in Puma to Swiss business <i>Cosa Liebermann SA</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Thomas_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Thomas-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2003">2003</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: 2003">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>For the fiscal year 2003, the company had revenue of €1.274&#160;billion. Puma was the commercial sponsor for the 2002 <a href="/wiki/Anime" title="Anime">anime</a> series <i><a href="/wiki/Hungry_Heart:_Wild_Striker" title="Hungry Heart: Wild Striker">Hungry Heart: Wild Striker</a></i>, with the jerseys and clothing sporting the Puma brand. Puma ranks as one of the top shoe brands with <a href="/wiki/Adidas" title="Adidas">Adidas</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nike,_Inc." title="Nike, Inc.">Nike</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2007">2007</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: 2007">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In February 2007 Puma reported that its profits had fallen by 26% to €32.8&#160;million ($43&#160;million; £22&#160;million) during the final three months of 2006. Most of the decline in profits was due to higher costs linked to its expansion; sales rose by more than a third to €480.6&#160;million.<sup id="cite_ref-BBC_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BBC-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In early April 2007 Puma's shares rose €29.25 per share, or about 10.2%, to €315.24 per share.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 10 April 2007 French retailer and owner of <a href="/wiki/Gucci" title="Gucci">Gucci</a> brand <a href="/wiki/PPR_(company)" class="mw-redirect" title="PPR (company)">Pinault-Printemps-Redoute</a> (PPR) announced that it had bought a 27% stake in Puma, clearing the way for a full takeover. The deal valued Puma at €5.3&#160;billion. PPR said that it would launch a "friendly" takeover for Puma, worth €330 a share, once the acquisition of the smaller stake was completed. The board of Puma welcomed the move, saying it was fair and in the firm's best interests.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of July 2007, PPR owned over 60% of Puma stock.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2011">2011</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: 2011">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In July 2011 the company completed a conversion from an <a href="/wiki/Aktiengesellschaft" title="Aktiengesellschaft">Aktiengesellschaft</a> (German <a href="/wiki/Public_company" title="Public company">public</a> limited company) to a <a href="/wiki/Societas_Europaea" title="Societas Europaea">Societas Europaea</a>, the <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">European Union</a>-wide equivalent, changing its name from <i>Puma AG Rudolf Dassler Sport</i> to <i>Puma SE</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> At the same time, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Franz_Koch_(businessman)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Franz Koch (businessman) (page does not exist)">Franz Koch</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&#160;&#91;<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Koch_(Manager)" class="extiw" title="de:Franz Koch (Manager)">de</a>&#93;</span> replaced the long-serving <a href="/wiki/Jochen_Zeitz" title="Jochen Zeitz">Jochen Zeitz</a> as the firm's chief executive officer, with Zeitz becoming chairman.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Since_2012">Since 2012</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Since 2012">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Puma holds a 5% stake at German sports club <a href="/wiki/Borussia_Dortmund" title="Borussia Dortmund">Borussia Dortmund</a>, whose supplier has been the company since 2012.
</p><p>The company has been led by former football professional Bjørn Gulden (chief executive officer) since 1 July 2013.
</p><p>Puma is the main producer of enthusiast driving shoes and race suits. They are the primary producer for <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> and <a href="/wiki/NASCAR" title="NASCAR">NASCAR</a> clothing. They won the rights to sponsor the <a href="/wiki/2006_FIFA_World_Cup" title="2006 FIFA World Cup">2006 FIFA World Cup</a> champions, the <a href="/wiki/Italy_national_football_team" title="Italy national football team">Italian national football team</a>, making and sponsoring the clothing worn by the team. They entered a partnership with <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ducati" class="mw-redirect" title="Ducati">Ducati</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari</a> to make Puma-Ferrari, Puma-Ducati and Puma-BMW shoes.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Rihanna" title="Rihanna">Rihanna</a> was named creative director of Puma overseeing direction of the womenswear line in December 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2014, Puma and <a href="/wiki/Arsenal_F.C." title="Arsenal F.C.">Arsenal Football Club</a> entered a 5-year merchandising partnership. The commercial partnership represents the biggest deal in Puma and Arsenal's history.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> The partnership ended in 2019.
</p><p>In March 2018, Puma launched its venture with its ambassador <a href="/wiki/Selena_Gomez" title="Selena Gomez">Selena Gomez</a> called "Phenom Lux''.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup> In 2018, Puma re-entered the basketball sneaker market for the first time in 20 years and announced <a href="/wiki/Jay-Z" title="Jay-Z">Jay-Z</a> will be the creative director for Puma Basketball. Puma last sponsored <a href="/wiki/Vince_Carter" title="Vince Carter">Vince Carter</a> in 1998. They signed young basketball players <a href="/wiki/Marvin_Bagley_III" title="Marvin Bagley III">Marvin Bagley III</a> and <a href="/wiki/Deandre_Ayton" title="Deandre Ayton">Deandre Ayton</a>, both of whom became the Top 2 picks of the <a href="/wiki/2018_NBA_Draft" class="mw-redirect" title="2018 NBA Draft">2018 NBA Draft</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In December 2018, Puma reintroduced the RS Computer, with "RS" standing for "running system." The shoe contains technologies such as an <a href="/wiki/Accelerometer" title="Accelerometer">accelerometer</a> and Bluetooth.
</p><p>In September 2020, Puma signed with Brazilian football superstar <a href="/wiki/Neymar" title="Neymar">Neymar</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Labor_practices_and_factory_conditions">Labor practices and factory conditions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Labor practices and factory conditions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In 2000, Puma began auditing all of its suppliers on a yearly basis, and makes the results available in its sustainability reports. Since 2005, it has publicly provided a list of its suppliers.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In August 2004, a joint report from the <a href="/wiki/National_Labor_Committee" class="mw-redirect" title="National Labor Committee">National Labor Committee</a> and <a href="/wiki/China_Labor_Watch" title="China Labor Watch">China Labor Watch</a> stated that workers at some of Puma's Chinese factories were enduring <a href="/wiki/Sweatshop" title="Sweatshop">sweatshop</a> conditions, working up to 16.5 hours per day for about US$0.31 an hour. Puma said they would investigate the claims.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In February 2012, a woman who worked for one of Puma's suppliers in <a href="/wiki/Cambodia" title="Cambodia">Cambodia</a> was shot during a protest over factory working conditions. Puma acknowledged the poor working conditions and said they would work to improve the situation.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>According to a joint report from <a href="/wiki/Labour_Behind_the_Label" title="Labour Behind the Label">Labour Behind the Label</a> and Community Legal Education Centre, 30 workers fainted in November 2012 while producing clothing for Puma in China. The faintings were caused by excessive heat and alleged forced overtime.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Washington_Post_2014_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Washington_Post_2014-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> In 2014, almost 120 workers fainted in two Cambodian clothing factories where sportswear was being produced for Puma and <a href="/wiki/Adidas" title="Adidas">Adidas</a>, due to temperatures above 100 degrees.<sup id="cite_ref-Washington_Post_2014_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Washington_Post_2014-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> In March 2017, 150 workers assembling Puma products in Cambodia fainted due to thick smoke.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Puma has obtained the Ethical Clothing Australia accreditation for its Australian-made products.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> This labour-friendly accreditation applies to only a small percentage of Puma's total production.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Environmental_practices">Environmental practices</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Environmental practices">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In May 2011, English newspaper <i><a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a></i> released an article saying that Puma was the "world's first major company to put a value on its environmental impact". According to the article the company "has made a commitment that within four years, half its international collections will be manufactured according to its internal sustainability standard, by using more sustainable materials such as recycled polyester, as well as ensuring its suppliers develop more sustainable materials and products."<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Puma is also known for boosting positive environmental practices in its supply chain through financial incentives. The innovative <a href="/wiki/Reverse_factoring" class="mw-redirect" title="Reverse factoring">Supply Chain Finance</a> scheme implemented links the sustainability performance of key suppliers to the costs at which they can access finance. Such scheme won the company an "Innovation Award" in <a href="/wiki/Supply_Chain_Finance" class="mw-redirect" title="Supply Chain Finance">Supply Chain Finance</a> in 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Timeline">Timeline</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Puma_(brand)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Timeline">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/de/Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG/220px-Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/de/Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG/330px-Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/de/Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG/440px-Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_Evopower_Goalkeeper_vs._Puma_Furio_Racing.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Puma goalkeeper gloves and Puma motorsport gloves.</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_shoes.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Puma_shoes.jpg/220px-Puma_shoes.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Puma_shoes.jpg/330px-Puma_shoes.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Puma_shoes.jpg/440px-Puma_shoes.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="683" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_shoes.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>A pair of Puma suede shoes,<br />a style introduced in 1968.</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_store_Osaka.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Puma_store_Osaka.jpg/220px-Puma_store_Osaka.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Puma_store_Osaka.jpg/330px-Puma_store_Osaka.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Puma_store_Osaka.jpg/440px-Puma_store_Osaka.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2042" data-file-height="1528" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Puma_store_Osaka.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Puma store in <a href="/wiki/Osaka" title="Osaka">Osaka</a>.</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG/220px-HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG/330px-HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG/440px-HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:HK_Tung_Chung_One_CityGate_shop_Puma_visitors_Oct-2012.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Puma LOO Kong.</div></div></div>
<ul><li>1920: <a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Dassler" title="Rudolf Dassler">Rudolf Dassler</a> and his brother <a href="/wiki/Adolf_Dassler" title="Adolf Dassler">Adolf</a> start making sports shoes.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1924: Foundation of Gebrüder Dassler Schuhfabrik, Herzogenaurach, Germany.<sup id="cite_ref-PUMA®_–_History_34-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PUMA®_–_History-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1930s: With the rise of Adolf Hitler in the 1930s, both Dassler brothers joined the Nazi Party, with Rudolf reputed as being the more ardent National Socialist.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> They produced boots for the Wehrmacht.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1948: The brothers split, forming Puma (at first, Ruda) and <a href="/wiki/Adidas" title="Adidas">Adidas</a>. In the same year, Puma's first football boot, the "Atom", was launched.</li>
<li>1952: Rudolf Dassler developed the "Super Atom", a football boot with screw-in studs.<sup id="cite_ref-PUMA®_–_History_34-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PUMA®_–_History-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1953: Development of <i>Atom'</i>s successor: the <i>Brasil.</i><sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1958: Puma introduced its trademark formstrip logo.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1959: The company is transformed into a <a href="/wiki/Limited_partnership" title="Limited partnership">limited partnership</a> named <i>Puma-Sportschuhfabriken Rudolf Dassler KG.</i><sup id="cite_ref-fundinguniverse.com_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fundinguniverse.com-63">&#91#91;63&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1960: Puma is the first sports shoe manufacturer to use <a href="/wiki/Vulcanization" title="Vulcanization">vulcanization</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-PUMA®_–_History_34-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PUMA®_–_History-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1970: A few months prior to the <a href="/wiki/1970_FIFA_World_Cup" title="1970 FIFA World Cup">1970 FIFA World Cup</a>, Armin Dassler (Rudolf's son) and his cousin, <a href="/wiki/Horst_Dassler" title="Horst Dassler">Horst Dassler</a> (Adi's son), sealed an agreement which was dubbed "The Pelé pact". This agreement dictated that soccer player <a href="/wiki/Pel%C3%A9" title="Pelé">Pelé</a> would be out of bounds for both Adidas and Puma. However, Pelé complied with a request by Puma's representative Hans Henningsen to increase the awareness and profile of Puma after he received $120,000 to wear the Formstrips.<sup id="cite_ref-rediff_28-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rediff-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> At the opening whistle of a 1970 World Cup finals match, Pelé stopped the referee with a last-second request to tie his shoelaces before kneeling down to give millions of television viewers a close-up of his Puma shoes.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmit200982_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmit200982-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup> This outraged Horst and future peace agreements were called off.</li>
<li>1972: Two years later, during the <a href="/wiki/1972_Summer_Olympics" title="1972 Summer Olympics">1972 Summer Olympics</a>, Puma provided shoes for the Ugandan <a href="/wiki/400_metres_hurdles" title="400 metres hurdles">400 metres hurdles</a> champion, <a href="/wiki/John_Akii-Bua" title="John Akii-Bua">John Akii-Bua</a>. After Akii-Bua was forced out of Uganda by its <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Uganda" title="Politics of Uganda">military government</a>, Puma employed him in Germany. Eventually Akii-Bua returned to Uganda.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1973: Launch of the <a href="/wiki/Puma_Clyde" title="Puma Clyde">Clyde</a>. Designed for basketball player <a href="/wiki/Walt_Frazier" title="Walt Frazier">Walt "Clyde" Frazier</a>, this model gained wide popularity.<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1974: <a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Dassler" title="Rudolf Dassler">Rudolf Dassler</a> died on 27 October. Both his sons Armin and Gerd inherited the company and after a legal dispute between the two, <a href="/wiki/Armin_Dassler" title="Armin Dassler">Armin Dassler</a> took over the company.<sup id="cite_ref-fundinguniverse.com_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fundinguniverse.com-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1976: Introduction of the S.P.A.-Technology.<sup id="cite_ref-fundinguniverse.com_63-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fundinguniverse.com-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1985: <a href="/wiki/Boris_Becker" title="Boris Becker">Boris Becker</a> helps develop the shoe that bears his name. <a href="/wiki/Martina_Navratilova" title="Martina Navratilova">Martina Navratilova</a> is under contract with Puma from 1984 to 1987.</li>
<li>1986: Transformation into a <a href="/wiki/Stock_corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="Stock corporation">stock corporation</a>. The company went public as "Puma AG" was listed on the Munich and Frankfurt stock exchanges.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1989: Launch of the <i>Trinomic</i> sport shoe system.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1989: Rudolf's sons Armin and Gerd Dassler agreed to sell their 72 percent stake in Puma to Swiss business Cosa Liebermann SA.<sup id="cite_ref-Thomas_36-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Thomas-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1990: Introduction of <i>Inspector</i>, a growth control system for children's shoes.</li>
<li>1991: Launch of the <i>Disc System</i> sports shoe.<sup id="cite_ref-PUMA®_–_History_34-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PUMA®_–_History-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1992: Capital increase by <a href="/wiki/Deutsche_Mark" title="Deutsche Mark">DM</a> 20 million, share capital reaches DM 70&#160;million.</li>
<li>1993: <a href="/wiki/Jochen_Zeitz" title="Jochen Zeitz">Jochen Zeitz</a> was appointed chief executive officer.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1994: The first profit since the company's initial public offering in 1986 is registered.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1996: Puma is listed in the German <a href="/wiki/MDAX" title="MDAX">M-DAX index</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> introduction of the <i>CELL </i>technology, the first foam-free midsole.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>1997: Launch of the <i>Cellerator.</i></li>
<li>1998: Puma signs <a href="/wiki/Serena_Williams" title="Serena Williams">Serena Williams</a>.</li>
<li>1999: Puma becomes an official on-field supplier of the <a href="/wiki/National_Football_League" title="National Football League">NFL</a>, a legacy reflected in the numeral font of the <a href="/wiki/Tennessee_Titans" title="Tennessee Titans">Tennessee Titans</a> jersey which still uses the original Puma design. Puma is the uniform manufacturer for both <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl" title="Super Bowl">Super Bowl</a> teams that year.</li>
<li>2000: Production of fireproof footwear in partnership with <a href="/wiki/Porsche" title="Porsche">Porsche</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sparco" title="Sparco">Sparco</a>.</li>
<li>2001: Acquisition of the Scandinavian Tretorn Group.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup> The Puma Speedcat is launched.</li>
<li>2002: Puma ends tenure as an on-field supplier for the NFL, when <a href="/wiki/Reebok" title="Reebok">Reebok</a> is announced as the league's sole official uniform and apparel sponsor for 10 years (2002-2011).<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> Puma and Serena Williams unveiled the "Serena Williams Tennis Collection".</li>
<li>2003: Majority shareholder Monarchy/Regency sells its shareholdings to a broad base of institutional investors.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2004: Collaborative partnership with designer <a href="/wiki/Philippe_Starck" title="Philippe Starck">Philippe Starck</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2005: Mayfair Vermögensverwaltungsgesellschaft mbh acquires a total of 16.91% shareholding.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2006: The company is listed in the Dow Jones Sustainability Index;<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup> Introduction of the S.A.F.E. concept, a specific tool developed to continuously improve social and environmental standards. Shoe collection in cooperation with <a href="/wiki/Alexander_McQueen" title="Alexander McQueen">Alexander McQueen</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2007: On 10 April, French retailer and owner of <a href="/wiki/Gucci" title="Gucci">Gucci</a> brand <a href="/wiki/PPR_(company)" class="mw-redirect" title="PPR (company)">Pinault-Printemps-Redoute</a> (PPR) announced that it had bought a 27% stake in Puma clearing the way for a full takeover. The deal valued Puma at €5.3 billion. PPR said that it would launch a "friendly" takeover for Puma, worth €330 a share, once the acquisition of the smaller stake was completed. The board of Puma welcomed the move, saying it was fair and in the firm's best interests.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup> Prolongation of the contract with Jochen Zeitz by five years.<sup id="cite_ref-about.puma.com_81-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-about.puma.com-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2008: <a href="/wiki/Melody_Harris-Jensbach" title="Melody Harris-Jensbach">Melody Harris-Jensbach</a> is appointed deputy chief executive officer; cesigner and artist <a href="/wiki/Hussein_Chalayan" title="Hussein Chalayan">Hussein Chalayan</a> becomes creative director,<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> Puma also acquires a majority stake in Chalayan's business and <i>Hussein Chalayan.</i><sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2010: Puma acquired Cobra Golf, which was renamed Cobra Puma Golf.<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> Puma became a carbon neutral company.</li>
<li>2011: Puma becomes a European corporation under the name of Puma SE. <a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Koch_(Manager)" class="extiw" title="de:Franz Koch (Manager)">Franz Koch</a> is named chief executive officer. Puma took over Bodywear and Socks company Dobotex. The company released the first Environmental Profit and Loss Account which valued Puma's environmental impact at 145 million euros.</li>
<li>2012: Signs an eight-year deal to make kits for <a href="/wiki/Borussia_Dortmund" title="Borussia Dortmund">Borussia Dortmund</a>, starting from the 2012–13 season.<sup id="cite_ref-Borussia_Dortmund_deal_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Borussia_Dortmund_deal-85">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2013: Bjørn Gulden is named chief executive officer.</li>
<li>2014: Puma announced a long-term deal with <a href="/wiki/Club_de_F%C3%BAtbol_Monterrey" class="mw-redirect" title="Club de Fútbol Monterrey">Club de Fútbol Monterrey</a>.</li>
<li>2014: Puma and <a href="/wiki/Arsenal_F.C." title="Arsenal F.C.">Arsenal Football Club</a> entered a long-term merchandising partnership. The commercial partnership represents the biggest deal in Puma and Arsenal's history.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2015: <a href="/wiki/Rihanna" title="Rihanna">Rihanna</a> became Puma's global ambassador for women's training as well as Puma Women's creative director. She directly influences product collections, designs and customizes classic Puma styles as well as creates new product lines.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2016: Puma became the official licensed partner and official supplier of team and racewear to <a href="/wiki/Red_Bull_Racing" title="Red Bull Racing">Red Bull Racing</a>. Puma partnered with <a href="/wiki/The_Weeknd" title="The Weeknd">The Weeknd</a> as a new Global Brand ambassador and creative collaborator.<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2016: Puma endorses its casual wear deal with <a href="/wiki/Virat_Kohli" title="Virat Kohli">Virat Kohli</a> as a new Cricket Brand ambassador and creative collaborator in India of worth ₨.110 crores.</li>
<li>2017: Puma released sneakers known as "Money in the Bank", in relation to <a href="/wiki/WWE" title="WWE">WWE</a>'s annual pay-per-view, <a href="/wiki/WWE_Money_in_the_Bank" title="WWE Money in the Bank">of the same name</a>.</li>
<li>2017: Puma signs a five-year deal to make kits for <a href="/wiki/Olympique_de_Marseille" title="Olympique de Marseille">Olympique de Marseille</a>, starting from the 2018–19 season.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2018: Kering announces it will spin off a 70% stake in Puma to its shareholders while retaining directly 16%.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2018: Puma collaborates with <a href="/wiki/Hello_Kitty" title="Hello Kitty">Hello Kitty</a> to launch the Puma X Hello Kitty For All Time collection.<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2018: Puma &amp; <a href="/wiki/A.C._Milan" title="A.C. Milan">A.C. Milan</a> announced an official long-term partnership, effective on 1 July 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2018: <a href="/wiki/BTS" title="BTS">BTS</a> became Puma's global ambassadors.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2018: Puma signs a three-year deal to make kits for <a href="/wiki/Sociedade_Esportiva_Palmeiras" title="Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras">Palmeiras</a>, starting from the 2019 season.<sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2018: Puma re-entry into the basketball sneaker category for the first time in 20 years and announced <a href="/wiki/Jay-Z" title="Jay-Z">Jay-Z</a> will be the creative director of Puma Basketball.<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">&#91;95&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2019: Puma and <a href="/wiki/City_Football_Group" title="City Football Group">City Football Group</a> signed a global long-term partnership, the deal is the largest deal both organisations have signed, the deal will see Puma supply <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City F.C.</a>, <a href="/wiki/Melbourne_City_FC" title="Melbourne City FC">Melbourne City FC</a>, <a href="/wiki/Girona_FC" title="Girona FC">Girona FC</a>, <a href="/wiki/Club_Atl%C3%A9tico_Torque" class="mw-redirect" title="Club Atlético Torque">Club Atlético Torque</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mumbai_City_FC" title="Mumbai City FC">Mumbai City FC</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sichuan_Jiuniu_F.C." title="Sichuan Jiuniu F.C.">Sichuan Jiuniu F.C.</a><sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96">&#91;96&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2019: Puma released a line called Puma X SG in collaboration with actress and singer <a href="/wiki/Selena_Gomez" title="Selena Gomez">Selena Gomez</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2019: Puma signs a three-year deal to make kits for <a href="/wiki/Valencia_CF" title="Valencia CF">Valencia CF</a>, starting from the 2019–20 season.<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">&#91;98&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2020: Puma announced a long-term deal with Dutch football club PSV Eindhoven.</li>
<li>2020: Puma signed a long-term deal with Brazilian football superstar <a href="/wiki/Neymar" title="Neymar">Neymar</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>2020: Puma announced a long-term deal with Ukrainian football club <a href="/wiki/FC_Shakhtar_Donetsk" title="FC Shakhtar Donetsk">FC Shakhtar Donetsk</a>.</li></ul>
